{{Politics of Egypt}} Egypt is divided, for the purpose of [[public administration]], according to a three-layer hierarchy and some districts are further subdivided, creating an occasional fourth-layer.
The top-level of the hierarchy are 27 governorates (singular: {{lang|arz|محافظة}} ''{{transl|arz|muḥāfẓa}}'', plural: {{lang|ar|محافظات}} ''{{transl|arz|muḥāfẓat}}''). The second-level, beneath and within governorates, are [[Markaz (country subdivision)|marakiz]] (singular: {{lang|ar|مركز}} ''{{transl|arz|markaz}}'', plural: {{lang|ar|مراكز}} ''{{transl|arz|marakiz}}'') or aqsam (singular: {{lang|arz|قسم}} ''qism'', plural: {{lang|arz|أقسام}} ''{{transl|arz|aqsam}})''. The third-level is composed of districts (singular: {{lang|arz|حي}} ''{{transl|arz|ḥay}}'', plural: {{lang|arz|أحياء}} {{transl|arz|aḥya'}}) and villages (singular: {{lang|arz|قرية}} ''{{transl|arz|qarya}}'', plural: {{lang|ar|قرى}} ''{{transl|arz|qura}}''). There is a governing structure at each of these levels.<ref name="USAID">{{cite web|title=Egypt: The Basic Village Services Program|url=https://pdf.usaid.gov/pdf_docs/PDAAR029.pdf|website=USAID|accessdate=19 October 2016|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019144503/https://pdf.usaid.gov/pdf_docs/PDAAR029.pdf|archivedate=19 October 2016|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Metz|first1=Helen Chapin|title=Egypt: A Country Study. Washington: GPO for the Library of Congress, 1990|date=1990|url=http://countrystudies.us/egypt/113.htm|accessdate=20 October 2016|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161103013525/http://countrystudies.us/egypt/113.htm|archivedate=3 November 2016|df=}}</ref> Districts may be further divided into sub-districts as a fourth-level.
There are also seven economic [[Regions of Egypt|regions]] for other planning purposes, as defined by the General Organization for Physical Planning (GOPP).
== Provincial divisions == {{Main article|Governorates of Egypt}}
[[Egypt]] is divided into 27 [[governorate]]s (muhāfazāt) and each has a capital and at least one city.<ref name=Statoids>{{cite web|title=Governorates of Egypt|url=http://www.statoids.com/ueg.html|website=Statoids|accessdate=16 October 2016|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161014002115/http://statoids.com/ueg.html|archivedate=14 October 2016|df=}}</ref> Each governorate is administered by a governor, who is appointed by the [[President of Egypt]] and serves at the president's discretion. Most governorates have a population density of more than one thousand per km², while the three largest have a population density of less than two per km².<ref name="CAPMAS">{{cite web|title=Inhabited Population Density By Governorate 1/7/2014|url=http://www.msrintranet.capmas.gov.eg/pdf/EgyptinFigures2015/EgyptinFigures/Tables/PDF/1-%20%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%83%D8%A7%D9%86/pop.pdf|website=CAPMAS Egyptian Figures 2015|accessdate=19 October 2016|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019093240/http://www.msrintranet.capmas.gov.eg/pdf/EgyptinFigures2015/EgyptinFigures/Tables/PDF/1-%20%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%83%D8%A7%D9%86/pop.pdf|archivedate=19 October 2015|df=}}</ref> The governorates of Egypt are: {{div col|colwidth=22em}} *[[Alexandria Governorate]] *[[Aswan Governorate]] *[[Asyut Governorate]] *[[Beheira Governorate]] *[[Beni Suef Governorate]] *[[Cairo Governorate]] *[[Dakahlia Governorate]] *[[Damietta Governorate]] *[[Faiyum Governorate]] *[[Gharbia Governorate]] *[[Giza Governorate]] *[[Ismailia Governorate]] *[[Kafr El Sheikh Governorate]] *[[Luxor Governorate]] *[[Matruh Governorate]] *[[Minya Governorate]] *[[Monufia Governorate]] *[[New Valley Governorate]] *[[North Sinai Governorate]] *[[Port Said Governorate]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Seat of a first-order administrative division|url=http://www.geonames.org/358619/port-said.html|website=Geonames|accessdate=20 October 2016|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170120203512/http://www.geonames.org/358619/port-said.html|archivedate=20 January 2017|df=}}</ref> *[[Qalyubia Governorate]] *[[Qena Governorate]] *[[Red Sea Governorate]] *[[Sharqia Governorate]] *[[Sohag Governorate]] *[[South Sinai Governorate]] *[[Suez Governorate]] {{div col end}}
== Municipal divisions == [[File:Map of Markazes of Egypt.png|thumb|200px|right|Map of Egypt's municipal divisions.]] At the municipal-level are markaz, kism, police-administered areas, and new cities. Generally, rural areas are divided into markaz whereas urban areas are divided into kism. As of 2013, there were 351 subdivisions, of which 177 were kism, 162 markaz, 9 new cities, and 3 police-administered areas. There are also unorganized areas in Alexandria, Aswan, Asyut, Beheira, Beni Suef, Cairo, Dakahlia, Damietta, Faiyum, Giza, Ismailia, Kafr El Sheikh, Luxor, Minya, Port Said, Qalyubia, Qena, Sharqia, Sohag, Suez governorates.<ref>{{cite web|title=Egypt Markazes|url=http://www.statoids.com/yeg.html|website=Statoids|accessdate=19 October 2016|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408190631/http://statoids.com/yeg.html|archivedate=8 April 2016|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Law|first1=Gwillim|title=Administrative Subdivisions of Countries: A Comprehensive World Reference, 1900 Through 1998|date=November 23, 1999|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-6097-7|url=https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0786407298/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o00_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1|accessdate=19 October 2016}}</ref>
